<HEAD>
<title>Issues: First Amendment/Political Correctness -- CIR</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/cir/pix/gavel2.gif">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<CENTER><img src="/cir/pix/issues.gif" alt="Staff"></CENTER>
<p>
<center>
<h2>First Amendment &amp; Political Correctness</h2>
<small>
<a href="#supreme">Supreme Court Cases</a><br>
<a href="#appeals">U.S. Court of Appeals Cases</a><br>
<a href="#district">U.S. District Court Cases</a>
</small>
</CENTER>
<BR><BR>
<a name="supreme"></a>
<dl>
<h3>Supreme Court</h3>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Rosenberger v. University of Virginia</STRONG></EM>
<dd>A State University denied a religious student newspaper the right to apply for activity funds on the same terms as other student groups on the grounds that doing so would violate the Establishment Clause.  CIR, representing the students, argued that a government entity must be evenhanded in granting benefits, and that discrimination based solely on the newspaper's viewpoint was a violation of the Free Speech Clause.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two lower Courts found for the University, but the Supreme Court reversed 5-4 and found for the Students.  Current status: Remanded back to District Court where matter is pending.
<P>For more information go to the:<BR>
<A HREF="/cir/cases/rosensct.html">Supreme Court Opinion</A><BR><A HREF="/cir/cases/rosencir.html">Fourth Circuit Opinion</A><BR>
<A HREF="/cir/cases/rosendct.html">District Court Opinion</A><BR>
<P>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Hurley v. Irish America Gay, Lesbian and Bisexual Group of Boston</STRONG></EM>
<dd>The Massachusetts Supreme Court held that a private parade organization was required under State anti-discrimination laws to include groups with a homosexual message despite their desire to exclude such messages.  CIR submitted an <EM>Amicus Brief
</EM> in support of the parade organizers arguing that the First Amendment did not allow the state to force citizens to include a message with which they did not agree.  The Supreme Court agreed and reversed the Massachusetts Supreme Court 9-0.
<P>Status: remanded to State Court for a new hearing.
For more information go to the:<BR>
<A HREF="/cir/cases/hurlsct.html">Supreme Court Opinion</A><BR>
<P>
<dt><EM><STRONG>R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul</STRONG></EM><BR>
<dd><A HREF="/cir/cases/ravsct.html">112 S. Ct. 2538 (1992)</A>
<P>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Wisconsin v. Mitchell</STRONG></EM>
<dd><A HREF="/cir/cases/wiscsct.html">113 S. Ct. 2194 (1993)</A>
<P>
<BR>
<a name="appeals"></a>
<dt><h2>U.S. Court of Appeals:</h2>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Colorado Taxpayers Union, Inc. v. Romer</STRONG></EM>
<dd><A HREF="/cir/cases/ctucir.html">963 F.2d 1393 (10th Cir. 1992)</A>
<P>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Fair Employment Counsel v. BMC 
Marketing</STRONG></EM><BR>
<dd>A private group (FEC) sent black and white "testers" to a local employment agency (BMC) to see if it could provoke discriminatory activity at the agency.  FEC determined its testers were treated differently and sought a cash settlement from BMC under threat of a federal discrimination lawsuit.  In one of the few cases where it has represented a defendant, CIR represented BMC arguing that the testers did not have standing to sue because they were not actually seeking employment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The District Court refused to grant summary judgment, but the Court of Appeals held that the testers did not have standing to sue.  Current status: after winning at the Court of Appeals level, defendants settled the remaining issues with plaintiffs.

<P>For more information, go to the:<BR>
<A HREF="/cir/cases/fecdc.html">DC Circuit Court Opinion</A><BR><A HREF="fec.dct">District Court Opinion</A><BR>
<P>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Iota Chi Chapter v. George Mason University</STRONG></EM>
<dd><A HREF="/cir/cases/iotacir.html">993 F.2d 386 (4th Cir. 1993)</A><BR>
<A HREF="/cir/cases/iotadct.html">773 F. Supp. 792 (E.D. Va. 1991)</A>
<P>
<BR>
<a name="district"></a>
<dt><h2>U.S. District  Court:</h2>
<dt><EM><STRONG>Gee v. Humphries</STRONG></EM>
<dd>A College professor was suspended without pay for making a single remark to his class that allegedly constituted "racial harassment."  CIR sued in District Court on the grounds that the suspension violated the First Amendment and Equal Protection.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The School, Florida A&M, ended the suspension after a motion for preliminary injunction.  Current status: pending before District Court.
<P>
<dt><EM><STRONG>White v. Julian</STRONG></EM><BR>
<dd>Three residents of a neighborhood in Berkeley, Cal. became concerned about the City's policy of developing multiple homeless shelters in their neighborhood without providing adequate support.  They raise community awareness through speaking at public meetings, publishing a newsletter, and even bringing suit to prevent one shelter conversion allegedly in violation of State law.  The Department of Housing and Urban Development began a harassing "investigation" of the residents telling them they
 were in violation of Housing laws for discriminating against the "handicapped" (drug addicts in the shelters are defined as handicapped) and threatened them with fines of up to $50,000 unless the ceased their protest activity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;CIR represents the neighbors in a lawsuit against HUD and several HUD employees for violating the neighbors' free speech rights through their abuse of HUD's investigatory powers.  Current status: HUD has ended its "investigation" but claims for damages and injunctive relief are pending in District Court.<BR>

</blockquote></blockquote>
<P><br>
<center><small><a href="/cir">CIR Home</a> | <a href="/cir/i-new.html">New</a> | <a href="/cir/about/contact.html">Contact</a></small></center><P>
</BODY>

