<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Vlahos: Revolution -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>Revolution</h2>
by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Vlahos">Michael Vlahos</a>
<P>
<P>
&#147;Revolution&#148; is one of those words.
<P>
Arguably, it is an American sacred word, like Freedom and Democracy,
Progress and Liberty.  But how we trivialize, and in turn, are
terrified by it!
<P>
It is a word perfect in its diminutive:  The HealthRider is a
&#147;revolutionary&#148; product;  Connecticut&#146;s state government
calls recycling &#147;the next American Revolution;&#148;  each
new electoral shift is hailed as a &#147;revolution.&#148;  We
like revolution as Progress Plus, as long as it stays in the comfort
zone of the familiar, and what we know as the good.  It is Big
Change we control.
<P>
Which is clearly what revolution is not.
<P>
We know this too, so we love the word, but we are afraid of it
too.  We love the revolution we made.  But after 1776 came 1789.
 Big Change was Shanghaied.  High-octane <I>Pilgrim&#146;s Progress</I>
was ditched for the <I>Beau Savage</I>, who led a descent into
the primitive, to The Terror.  Our sober, civic revolution was
stolen by firebrand French wordsmiths.
<P>
And the word itself was abducted too.  Passed from Robspierre
to Rosa, from Lenin to Stalin to the Khmer Rouge, the word has
stayed blood-red, like the roses, cockades, and little red books
that are its symbols.
<P>
We Americans have never recaptured revolution.  We lay claim only
to a patch of thin turf by the great shore, that strip of change
at the edge of Progress.  We are wary now, even afraid, of change
beyond Progress.  We no longer know what to do with revolution.
<P>
But we cannot escape it.  Big change is here:  brought not by
barbarians at the gate, but by ourselves.  We are the barbarians
of big change.  We are the red-capped <I>sans culottes</I>.
<P>
America is again making revolution, and spreading it across the
world.  This revolution should not be confused with political
plots or electoral sallies against an Old Order.  This revolution
is much bigger than that;  like the industrial revolution, it
promises a transformation of America life.  But as tidally overwhelming
as it feels, it is no less of our own making.  And clearly, there
are those who are making it happen, just as there are those who
would sacrifice everything to hold its onset back just one more
day.  Like any revolution.
<P>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation&#146;s monthly lunches offer
us a chance to talk about Big Change as revolution.  They were
inspired by the fermentive talk that came before the first Bastille
Day&#150;those notorious <I>salons</I>&#150;but they are not meant
to imitate the outcome.  The logo roses on our <I>Notes From Salon
&#145;89</I> are meant to remind us of two things.  First that,
though it was stolen way back when, the word is now up for recapture.
 And second, the shock of other times tells us that revolution
is not about freeze frame shots from <I>Dr. Zhivago</I> or <I>A
Tale of Two Cities</I>.  Revolution is not some far away, long
ago story, so removed from us as to be nothing more than material
for a Hollywood meringue.
<P>
Revolution waits in the wings of every age.  It comes rarely,
but it comes for a reason.  Revolution is the moment when change
long pent up at last tears the fabric of life;  when all the elements
that allow us daily to accommodate to change, for a moment, fail.
 Revolution is the brief, free space between two worlds, and our
time in that space allows us to make the journey from old to new.
<P>
And who knows?  Perhaps Progress will prevail somehow, and the
Big Change will be managed and massaged so that, when it is over,
we never knew what happened.  It is possible.
<P>
Every fiber of mind teases and coaxes us down that road.  But
we don&#146;t need to worry about continuity:  we must confront
the equally possible prospect of its <I>absence</I>.
<P>
And to see possibility, we need to recapture the word:  Revolution.
 Part of that comes when we talk about it &#133; which is what
we intend to keep doing at our lunches.
<P>
We hope you will let us know if you are interested in joining
us.

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
