<HEAD>

<TITLE>Whose Values Mr. President? -- PFF</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Rick F. O'Donnell">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Michael Sparks">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Whose Values Mr. President?</h2>
By <a href="/pff/people/staff.html#O_Donnell">Richard F. O'Donnell</a>
</center><P>
<P>
 Bill Clinton has left the Republicans speechless.  For months
now, every time the President said he wanted a budget reflecting
and upholding American values, Republicans responded they wanted
a budget balanced in seven years with real numbers.  Clinton finally
met their demand, producing a plan that he says balances the budget
<I>and</I> reflects American values.
<P>
 Calling his plan too &quot;liberal&quot; every time the President
tells Americans he is protecting Medicare, education and the environment
is not going to win the GOP many points in the court of public
opinion.  As part of a winning public relations strategy, Republicans
must answer head on each of the President's claims.
<P>
 Bill Clinton needs to be asked whose values he is claiming to
uphold in his Medicare proposals.  Are they the values of elderly
Americans relying on a healthcare program that even Clinton's
own advisers told him last spring faces bankruptcy without major
changes?  Are they the values of working Americans who will see
their payroll taxes continue to rise to unbearable heights to
fund an out-of-control cost spiral of a program? Or is Bill Clinton
still promoting the values of Ira Magaziner, who believes a one-size-fits-all
bureaucratic health care system directed from Washington is the
best way for millions of Americans' healthcare decisions to be
made?
<P>
 Bill Clinton needs to be asked whose values he is claiming to
uphold in his education proposals.  Are they the values of parents
desperately seeking empowerment to choose the finest schools for
the education of their children? Or is Bill Clinton promoting
the values of the educational guild of tenured-teachers and politically
correct professors who want to nationalize education - taking
decisions away from communities - and force on children a skewed
view of history that denigrates heroes and celebrates supposed
victims?
<P>
 Bill Clinton needs to be asked whose values he is upholding in
his environmental proposals.  Are they the values of farmers,
ranchers, hikers and nature lovers across America who daily interact
with, are a part of and intimately understand their ecosystem
and want their children to enjoy its benefits also?  Or is Bill
Clinton promoting the values of EPA bureaucrats who, from cement
towers in Washington, D.C., call humans unnatural and purport
to know more about the forests of Oregon or the shores of Cape
Cod or the wetlands of Missouri than people whose families have
lived there for generations?
<P>
 Bill Clinton needs to be asked why he only wants tax relief for
working families.  Why not for job creators? Why not for investors
who take risks in creating new business ventures and growing the
American economy?
<P>
 In the lists of items the President says he wants to protect
is a significant omission:  welfare.  Although Clinton may hate
the GOP version of welfare reform, he knows the middle class wants
reform and the GOP has captured the moral high ground. Republicans
are protecting American values by replacing a system that discourages
work, forces people to live in housing fit only for rats and denies
generation after generation of our fellow citizens those rights
endowed to them by our Creator.
<P>
 Bill Clinton has been winning public sentiment because he is
claiming to protect and uphold the values of the middle class.
 Republicans should have reminded the President the past few months
that they want a budget balanced with real numbers because <I>they
too</I> are protecting American values:  those of thrift that
hold the government should balance its books, live within its
means and not mortgage our children's and grandchildren's future.
<P>
 It is time for the Republicans to ask Bill Clinton:  &quot;Whose
values are you protecting?  Those of normal Americans or those
of a politically correct, imperial elite with whom you communed
at Renaissance Weekend?&quot;  Such language will inflame liberal
journalists across the land, but the majority of Americans who
were <I>not</I> at Hilton Head will understand.
<P>
 The values Bill Clinton is claiming to protect are not those
of the middle class.  Americans are demanding the freedom to think
and choose for themselves how to live their lives without a bloated,
remote, debt-ridden government taxing and regulating them to death.
 This is what the '94 Revolution was all about.  These are Republican
values; they are nothing to be ashamed of and Republicans should
start defending them.
<P>
Republicans should not let Bill Clinton get away with claiming
he is protecting American values and they are not; it is time
for the President to be challenged and made to defend his values.
 This will assist in turning the debate away from the supposedly
&quot;mean spirited&quot; GOP efforts to reduce the size and scope
of government to why Bill Clinton is trying to preserve big, bureaucratic
government that does not represent the American people.
<P></blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
</BODY>

</HTML>
