<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Vlahos:  Are We Reliving the 1850s?  -- PFF</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Compaq Computer Owner">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Michael Manning">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <a href="/pff/"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" border="0" align="right"></a>
<center>

<P>
<h2>Are We Reliving the 1850s?</h2>
<P>
by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.htm#Vlahos">Michael Vlahos</a>
</center><P>
 <ul><blockquote>
The Big Election fanned The Talk.  Now everyone in town was asking,
is the realignment that comes every two or three generations really
upon us?  Is this the next Big Change in American politics?
<P>
And the next question was always:  Which realignment?  Is this
one more like 1932 or 1896?  Long wave theories trotted out. 
Names like Hanna and Bryan were heard again.
<P>
But with Oklahoma City and Waco, murmurs of the 1850s began to
lace The Talk.  On the evening of the Million Man March, the Speaker
of the House came right out and said it:  today is like the 1850s.
<P>
The 1850s were scary times.  People killed for ideology, called
the government corrupt and tyrannical, and dreamed draconian national
solutions.  
<P>
But it still looks like a pretty superficial stretch ... that
is, until I read Bill Gienapp's <I>Origins of the Republican Party,
1852-56.  </I>He tells a riveting story, a remarkable feat for
600-odd pages in micronic font, broken only by maps of county-by-county
voting.  Why is it so compelling?
<P>
Because even when you get down to details, the talk and feel of
another time:  it reads like today.
<P>
I wanted to put this historical deja vu to the test, so I sought
out Professor Gienapp.  I wanted to lay out all the leaping associations
and harmonic resonances, and see what the sober historian would
have to say.
<P>
Here, in thumbnail, is how it went.  I started by laying out the
case:
<ul><P>
<B>The Dem's in 1852.</B>
<P>
We like to talk about how Democrats have dominated politics since
the New Deal.  But the Democracy of the 1850's [as they liked
to call themselves] had run the show since America began.  In
1860, we could look back on slave-owning presidents for 50 our
our first 71 years.  The majority of Speakers of the House, of
Presidents <I>Pro Tem</I>;  and <I>always</I>, a majority of the
Supreme Court, was Southern.  The Southern Democrat vision of
American politics <I>was</I> American politics.
<P>
<B>The Economic Revolution.</B>
<P>
We are abuzz with an Information Revolution.  But Americans then
were laboring to adjust to something even more elemental:  an
Industrial Revolution.  The Big Change that would transform American
life was just starting its sweep in the 1850's, as the great urban
migration hit railroad stride.  City populations doubled and tripled:
 New York went from 20% urban in 1850 to 40% in 1860.  And the
yeoman farmer was being displaced by the factory worker.  In 1860,
wage laborers for the first time equaled the self-employed.  And
the new world was being built in the North.  The South was being
left behind ... along with its grip on political power.
<P>
<B>The Death of the Whigs.</B>
<P>
For decades the Whigs had been the second party:  the party of
economic growth.  But they had lived under the shadow of the Democrats,
and having made their compact with The Democracy, they dared not
challenge the arrangements that gave Democrats political sway.
 But the narrow fiscal issues around which they had crafted their
platform had all dried up.  Whigs had nothing to say to people
in the new world being made by railroad and mill.  Does this remind
us just a bit of our own Country Club Republicans?  Having nothing
to say, the Whigs crashed and burned in the election of 1992;
 I mean, 1852.
<P>
<B>The <I>Know Nothings</I>.</B>
<P>
From the wreckage of the Whigs came two new parties.  By far the
biggest, representing regular people in both North and South,
was the North American Party, who also styled themselves <I>Know
Nothings</I>.  These were people who saw their way of life eroding,
their hope for the future slipping away.  Economic revolution
was creating a new world of wage labor, of industrial slums, and
of job competition with the millions of immigrants pouring into
American life.  <I>Know Nothings</I> were anti-immigrant and anti-Catholic,
much the way workers today are anti-immigrant and anti-UN/NAFTA/WTO,
where the immigrant is the embodiment of large change threatening
their job, and where the foreign institution poking into American
life threatens liberty itself.  Their ranks are filled with Protestant
evangelicals, and their vision is full of nostalgia for a better,
truer, American Dream from a world gone by.
<P>
<B>The New Republicans.</B>
<P>
The Republicans, in contrast, come as the party of revolution.
 They looked to the future, and to a renewed American Dream. 
Their ranks were flush with old abolitionists, once marginal to
the political scene, who now saw their chance to bring sacred
principles to the center of politics [they acted a little like
some Libertarians we know].  And they have the support of new
money, the new entrepeneurs of the industrial age.  Money flows
in from the high technologies, the <I>parvenu</I> corporations
built on iron rails.  But Republicans have a problem: the <I>Know
Nothings</I> are a majority in the North.  How to woo them, how
to make a new national party - not like the old Whigs, built on
fiscal probity, nor like the <I>Know Nothings</I>, on nativism
- but on a new vision of American life?
<P>
<B>The Issue.</B>
<P>
We still think the issue was slavery ... getting rid of it, that
is.  The truth is  Republicans did something very different. 
They ditched whining, moralistic cries for abolition.  They said
instead:  <I>The ruling Old Order of Democrats and comprador Whigs
is a monster, slowly robbing Americans </I>[white male voters]<I>
of their liberty.  And because it is on the defensive, it has
turned aggressive, so it must be stopped now</I>.  And Republicans
called this Old Order, <I>The Slave Power</I>, the vested interest
of the past, European in its concept of hierarchy and rule, and
so inimical to American virtue and the American idea.  What this
meant is that Republicans took people's fears of change and uncertainty
about their future, which had fastened on a mix of neighborhood
scapegoats [immigrants] and ethereal tyrannies [the Catholic Church],
and turned them on the reigning political elite and its paradigm
of rule.  It took the Christian right of 1854 and said:  to get
to a better America, to renew the American Dream, we must first
destroy <I>The Slave Power</I>. 
<P>
Looking back, what will people say about us?  Can we frame the
battle as well as those first Republicans?
<P>
<B>The Talk.</B>
<P>
Paranoid politics?  Why, yes.  As Gienapp points out through his
narrative, it is the heart of American political tradition.  Our
first revolution made it so.  In the nineteenth century the big
conflicts in American politics were all conspiracies directed
against Liberty.  For the Jacksonians, it was the Banks.  For
the Whigs, it was the power of the Executive Branch.  For the
<I>Know Nothings</I>, it was the Catholic Church.  And for Republicans,
it was the Southern-dominated political system.  Conspiracies
against Liberty hearken back to our founding, and before our founding,
as the earliest Americans sought to escape European tyrants. 
It was inevitable that the main threat to Liberty would eventually
arise at home, from among our own.  People believed this ... <I>and
still do</I>:  it is an existential theme in America's Pilgrim's
Progress.  And set against a general backdrop of uncertainty and
upheaval in national life, the retro-look and feel of the Southern
political paradigm (and its manifest failure to lead nationally)
cried out for definition.  And define it the Republicans did.
   
<P>
The Democracy entered yet another administration in 1856, owning,
again, both houses of Congress and the Presidency.  But theirs
was a weak, pusillanimous Commander-in-Chief, whose venality and
corruption was exposed to all in 1860.  Republican success in
defining Democrats as an Old Order elite standing in the way of
progress, liberty, and America's future was there for everyone
to see in the mid-term election of 1858, when they swept Congress.
<P>
Here are some swatches from Gienapp on early Republican ideology:
<P>
At the heart of free labor ideology was the idea that every man,
as Abraham Lincoln phrased it, had a right to rise economically
and socially to the limit of his ability  ...  Upholding the reality
of the American dream, the free labor ideal represented the optimistic
side of the Republican appeal.
<P>
or,
<P>
As a heritage of the American Revolution ... the ideology of republicanism
... included the fear of concentrated power ... and the belief
that such power was the natural enemy of liberty and if unchecked
would eventually destroy it.
<P></ul>
Still<I> deja vu?</I>
<P><ul>
<I><B>What doesn't work.</B></I>
<P>
Well, not quite.  Uncompromising as historian, Gienapp restrained
this writer's rush to neatly tie things up.  He sees three dissonances
especially that should keep us from claiming immediate kinship
with Seward, Greeley, Chase, Sumner, and Lincoln. 
<P>
      
<P>
<B>The Voter and Voting.</B>
<P>
Who voted in the 1850's.  That's easy:  white men.  But there's
more.  These were very young white men, and they were deeply engaged
in politics.  They may not have had as much formal schooling,
but they knew the issues better than most of us today.  They lived
politics, chewed politics;  rallies and parades were their theater,
their TV.  It was cool to be hot and partisan, and these were
aggressive young men.  Look at their sacrifice in war just ahead.
<P>
Contrast that voter profile to today's.  The age pyramid is geting
stood on its head, and people who actually vote are much, much
older.  Hardly a revolutionary cadre.  And how we vote is different
too.  Government did not control voting:  in the 1850's, anyone
could print up a ballot and vote.  So it was easy for new parties
to emerge.  After 1900, the two parties have worked together to
control, to keep others out.  Gienapp puts it this way:  imagine
if Colin Powell, rather than slogging through the primaries, could
just hand out ballots!
<P>
<B>Party decomposition.</B>
<P>
And though the Whigs of 1852 could have stood in nicely for George
Bush, the debacle of 1992 did not lead to the party's fall.  It's
all still there,  Old Whigs, <I>Know Nothings</I>, and radical
Republicans, all under the same umbrella.  But keeping a lid on
means that instead of rollicking chaos, forcing creativity, and
then creating a new vision, Republicans shoulder on as the Grand
<I>Old</I> Party with three visions:  one Democrat-comprador,
one a nostalgia-mongering return to The Golden Age, and one of
revolution.  The old order Democrats, flat on their backs, thus
still survive.  In weak niches, like the presidency, they may
even flourish.
<P>
  
<P>
<B>The Issue as Talk.</B>
<P>
And where is slavery?  So many other features seem to be in place:
 the economic revolution, the fears of regular people, the obdurate,
grasping control of a dying elite.  But two things that make one
are missing.
<P>
The first is a driving vision of America's future.  True, the
first Republicans didn't have that at first.  They were all negative,
their issues all about stopping the power of government gone wrong,
dismantling the structures of that power itself.  But after 1856,
they became more positive.  Their slogan, <I>Free Men, Free Labor,
Free Soil</I>, had a message:  that economic change, however unsettling,
would offer more opportunity, more wealth, and more freedom to
all Americans.  They promised a renewal of the American Dream.
<P>
But that renewal would never happen as long as <I>The Slave Power</I>
stood in the way.  Its entire energy was intent on stopping change,
on cementing its control over American life and liberty.  <I><B>Progress</B></I>
and <I><B>Anti-Progress</B></I> were thus symbolically intertwined
as political message.
<P>
Some resonances to this message leaked out of the Great Health
Care Debate of 1994.  The Old Order was clearly painted as attempting
to aggressively extend its social-bureaucratic vision in order
to entrench its power.  People came close to politically visualizing
a contemporary counterpart to the old Slave Power in the form
of a national ruling class centered in Washington <I>[in one national
poll from November, 1994, Americans 2-1 said that Washington was
an imperial city ruled by an imperial class].</I> 
<P>
But since that election, the lines have blurred again.  The Democracy
was visited by, and made, huge mistakes in the 1850s, from Bloody
Kansas to the caning of Sumner.  Southern Democrats let the new
Republicans define them.  Today's old order is much more sly.
<P>
Perhaps it is too soon to talk loosely about the 1850s.  We may
be knee-deep in economic revolution, but it's not flood stage
yet.  But just wait until it threatens the brittle dikes of the
old politics, and its <I>ancien regime</I>. 
<P>
Then, on the [next] net, maybe we'll be printing our own ballots
again.
</ul><P>
<center>
<P>

</center></blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
