<html>
<head>
<title>THE HERITAGE FOUNDATION BUDGET</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>The Heritage Foundation</h2>
<i>Number of Cabinet Agencies Would Shrink from 14 to 5</i>
<hr>
<h2>HERITAGE BUDGET PLAN PROPOSES "TOP-TO-BOTTOM" 
REORGANIZATION OF FEDERAL GOVERNMENT</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
WASHINGTON, APRIL 17, 1995 -- While almost everybody in the 
nation's capital, from President Clinton to House Speaker Newt Gingrich, 
continues to talk about "reinventing" or slimming down government, The 
Heritage Foundation today offered a comprehensive and detailed plan for 
actually doing so.<p>
The ambitious proposal, released today in draft form, "examines every 
nook and cranny of the $1.6 trillion federal enterprise," a spokesman for 
the prominent think tank said. Every agency and every program within 
each agency was "put to the test."<p>
The Heritage Foundation plan was characterized by Vice President Stuart 
Butler as a "federalism budget" because many responsibilities would be 
transferred to state and local government. In putting the plan together, he 
said, a team of analysts conducted a Peter Drucker-style top-to-bottom 
review of the entire federal government<p>
The plan, according to budget expert Scott Hodge, would: 1) balance the 
federal budget by the year 2000, two years earlier than would have been 
required under the balanced-budget amendment, while providing $152 
billion in tax relief to families with children, business and the elderly; 2) 
end corporate welfare; 3) close down obsolete and wasteful programs, 
strengthen core programs that are legitimate functions of government, 
and transfer functions that "are not proper federal activities" to the states 
or the private sector; and 4) create several new agencies as part of the 
consolidation process.<p>
<center><h3>Medicare, Foreign Aid, Defense</center></h3><p>
To promote economic growth, the Heritage budget plan calls for cutting 
the effective capital gains tax rate in half; allowing businesses the 
equivalent of writing off capital investments in the year in which they are 
made, rather than stretching out the deductions; and creating new 
"Individual Retirement-Plus Accounts," which would provide tax-free 
income upon retirement (though contributions to such accounts would not 
be tax-deductible).<p>
Social Security would not be touched. Medicare, however, would 
undergo major surgery, offering to retirees a variety of medical plans and 
choices, similar to those enjoyed by federal employees and members of 
Congress under the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program.
Changes and cuts in the foreign-aid program would result in savings of 
$10 billion to $14.6-billion over five years.<p>
In keeping with the Heritage Foundation's view that the first priority of 
the federal government is to defend the nation and secure U.S. interests 
abroad, defense spending would be maintained at current levels, adjusted 
for inflation. This is about $130 billion more than the administration has 
called for over the next five years.<p>
Heritage analysts consistently have argued that the Clinton administration 
has underfunded its own defense plan, known as the "Bottom-Up 
Review," by some $100 billion over five years. The General Accounting 
Office (GAO) has placed the shortfall even higher, at $150 billion.<p>
House and Senate leaders have more or less gone along with the 
administration's funding plans. Heritage Foundation analysts, however, 
believe this is a mistake, arguing that funding at such low levels would 
require the United States to withdraw more forces from Europe or Asia. It 
also would mean leaving the United States vulnerable to ballistic missile 
attack. To fully fund the Bottom-Up Review force, the Heritage budget 
would add the needed $100 billion to the Clinton administration's 
proposed five-year defense budget, plus $30 billion for such new 
initiatives as ballistic-missile defense. (The Heritage Foundation is 
expected to publish its own missile-defense plan next month.)<p>
<center><h3>Top-to-Bottom Structural Reorganization</center></h3><p>
Butler said the Heritage plan would allow U.S. taxpayers to spend far 
more of their own money, rather than sending it to Washington for 
bureaucrats to spend. "The public realizes that the federal government is 
too expensive, mired in debt, and does a poor job of carrying out its core 
functions, while doing many things it shouldn't do. They want this to 
stop. That was the message of both the 1992 and 1994 elections. The 
Clinton administration has proposed nothing that would change 
fundamentally the way government works -- or its cost." What is needed, 
instead, Butler said -- and what The Heritage Foundation will present to 
Congress when the House and Senate return from their recess -- is a plan 
for the kind of "top-to-bottom structural reorganization" many businesses 
have undertaken in recent years.<p>
If the Heritage plan were fully implemented, Butler said, the number of 
Cabinet level departments of government would be reduced from 14 to 
five (Defense, Health and Human Services, Justice, State and the 
Treasury). The Departments of Agriculture and Interior would be 
reorganized and reduced to sub-cabinet level independent agencies. The 
Department of Energy's nuclear-weapons programs and veterans 
programs now administered by the Department of Veterans Affairs would 
be shifted to the Department of Defense. <p>
Three major independent agencies -- the Federal Communications 
Commission, Interstate Commerce Commission and Small Business 
Administration -- would disappear entirely. The Departments of 
Commerce, Education, Housing and Urban Development (HUD), Labor, 
and Transportation -- like Energy and Veterans Affairs -- would be 
closed down, though some of their functions, as part of the overall 
streamlining and consolidation process, would be shifted to the states or 
moved elsewhere within the federal government.<p>
The new agencies proposed by The Heritage Foundation would 
consolidate various functions now scattered throughout the bureaucracy. 
Government research and data-collection functions, for example, would 
be moved from the Census Bureau (part of the slated-for-extinction 
Commerce Department), Bureau of Labor Statistics (Labor Department), 
and other agencies to a new Bureau of National Statistics. According to 
Butler, "An important purpose of this change is to house these functions 
within an agency characterized by a new ethos -- dispassionate data 
collection -- rather than within departments driven by policy-making."
Similarly, various environmental and land-management functions, now 
housed at the Departments of Agriculture and Interior, would be 
consolidated within a new Bureau of Natural Resources.<p>
Total spending reductions over five years would amount to more than 
$750 billion net. There also would be a net saving of $97 billion in 
interest on the national debt by the time the deficit is eliminated in the 
year 2000. (The Heritage Foundation report calculates future spending 
levels three different ways: using l) direct year-to-year spending 
comparisons, 2) government "baseline" spending projections, and 3) 
baseline projections, plus revenue from privatization and asset sales. 
Washington has been using the second method, measuring everything 
against a projected spending baseline.)<p>
<center><h3>Step-by-Step Instructions</center></h3><p>
Unlike the Clinton administration's and other budget proposals now being 
"vetted" in Washington, most of which focus solely on budget 
"functions" and costs, The Heritage Foundation blueprint provides 
Washington with step-by-step instructions on how to make the necessary 
changes.<p>
"It is very easy to say, 'Shut down the Departments of Commerce, 
Education, Energy, Labor, and Transportation and board up their doors.' 
But the process is far more complicated than that, so lawmakers need 
realistic advice on how you actually close down a government agency." 
Butler noted, "Some functions of these departments and the other 
agencies identified for extinction are necessary and proper, and worth 
continuing. The bureaucratic edifices within which these isolated 
programs now operate, however, are totally unnecessary and should be 
eliminated." Butler added that Heritage analysts already have been 
working with congressional task forces on how to conduct "radical 
surgery" on the government.<p>
<center><h3>Federalism, Privatization, Reorganization, Elimination</center></h3><p>
The Heritage budget plan was written by a team of analysts including 
Scott Hodge, Grover M. Hermann Fellow in Federal Budgetary Affairs, 
Ronald Utt, a visiting fellow and former director of privatization 
programs for the Office of Management and Budget, and Baker Spring, 
Heritage's senior defense policy analyst.<p>
To accomplish the objective of balancing the budget by the year 2002, 
while providing taxpayers with a "fiscal responsibility (tax-cut) 
dividend," the plan would:<p>
Limit the overall rate of increase in federal spending to just over 1 
percent per year. "Capping total spending [increases] ... does not mean 
every program must grow at that rate," Butler said. "It means that, taken 
together, programs cannot exceed that limit. If some high-priority 
programs grow faster," he added, "others must grow more slowly and 
others may have to be terminated." If Congress can't muster the political 
courage to make the cuts needed to stay within the legally binding 
ceiling, a bipartisan spending reduction commission -- similar to the 
military base-closing commission -- would be appointed, rather than 
instituting an across-the-board "sequester."<p>
Transfer to state and local governments programs more appropriately 
carried out at those levels of government. For example, more than 70 
means-tested anti-poverty programs, currently administered by the 
Departments of Agriculture, Education, Energy, Health and Human 
Services, and Housing and Urban Development, would be included in a 
new welfare block grant that would be given to the states. The Heritage 
Foundation plan also would transfer most federal lands to the states, 
except for national parks and wilderness areas that are deemed to be "of 
national significance," and end the "earmarking" of funds for local 
transportation and other projects.<p>
Butler explained: "Congress should enact a federal budget that makes 
clear that the first responsibility of the federal government is an adequate 
national defense. Congress then should examine every other program to 
determine whether it is truly national in scope and can be carried out on a 
national scale only by the federal government. Funding for all agencies 
and programs that don't meet this test, such as many education, welfare, 
health (and) transportation ... programs should be transferred to the states, 
or the money returned to the people as federal tax relief."<p>
Privatize all commercial activities of government. The proposal calls for 
the sale of the following federal assets: the $200 billion federal direct-
loan portfolio; Amtrak; the federal Power Marketing Administrations; the 
hydroelectric dams currently operated by the Army Corps of Engineers 
and Bureau of Reclamation; most of the National Weather Service; the 
Naval Petroleum Reserve, Strategic Petroleum Reserve, Federal Helium 
Reserves, and U.S. Uranium Enrichment Corporation; many real-estate 
holdings; and most of the 1,200 non-defense aircraft owned by the 
government.<p>
Eliminate corporate welfare. The Heritage Foundation budget plan would 
terminate dozens of programs that directly or indirectly subsidize private 
businesses, including all agricultural subsidies and commercial 
agricultural research programs, energy research programs, NASA's 
commercial aeronautic research and development programs, export credit 
guarantee programs, and export enhancement and "market promotion" 
programs. Also headed for the chopping block: Airport Grants-in-Aid 
and Essential Air Service Program (Transportation Department), Bureau 
of Export Administration (Commerce), Corporation for Public 
Broadcasting (independent), Economic Development Administration 
(Commerce), Farmers Home Administration and Farm Credit System 
(Agriculture), International Trade Administration (Commerce), Minority 
Business Development Agency (Commerce), Next Generation High-
Speed Rail Program (Transportation), Small Business Administration 
(independent), and U.S. Travel and Tourism Administration (Commerce). 
All government ties and taxpayer guarantees to the Federal Home Loan 
Bank System, Federal National Mortgage Association, Federal Home 
Loan Mortgage Corp., and Government National Mortgage Association 
would be terminated.<p>
End programs that don't work, "have become outmoded or obsolete, that 
duplicate other programs, or that do not involve legitimate government 
functions."<p>
"Because outmoded, obsolete, or inefficient programs almost never die, 
bureaus, agencies and programs that duplicate each other's function's 
have sprung up all over the government," Butler observed. Vice President 
Al Gore's National Performance Review, for example, noted that 14 
separate government departments and agencies spend $24 billion a year 
on 150 employment and training programs; 11 different federal 
departments and agencies administer 340 separate programs for families 
and children; and the Department of Commerce shares its mission with at 
least 7l federal departments, agencies and offices.<p>
The Heritage Foundation budget plan would close down many of the 
government's 1,200 "independent commissions, councils and boards," 
would sharply reduce the size and scope of the 170-year-old Army Corps 
of Engineers, and would close down, among other agencies, the 85-year-
old Bureau of Mines (Interior Department), 81-year-old Agricultural 
Extension Service (Agriculture), the 60-year-old Soil Conservation 
Service (Agriculture: now called the Natural Resource Conservation 
Service), the 60-year-old Rural Electrification Administration 
(Agriculture: now called the Rural Utilities Service); the 70-year-old 
National Fertilizer Development Center (part of the independent 
Tennessee Valley Authority: now called the TVA Environmental 
Research Center), and the 108-year-old Interstate Commerce 
Commission (independent).<p>
Butler said, "This is not the time to be timid. The federal government 
now consists of layer upon layer of bureaucratic waste, duplication and 
inefficiency. This was documented during the Reagan era by the Grace 
Commission and more recently by Vice President Gore's National 
Performance Review. "In addition, the federal bureaucracy has been 
assigned, or has assigned to itself, numerous tasks that are best left to the 
states, the private sector, or individuals.<p>
"Rather than tinkering at the margins, Washington needs to act with 
intelligence and resolve. We hope the Heritage budget plan will inspire 
the Congress and White House to accept the challenge."<p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
</body>
